    &gt; 
    &gt; 
    &gt; While that is all true, I haven&#39;t seen a need for it.  
    &gt; Maybe that&#39;s due to
    &gt; my limited use of Java (a little over a year).  Can you 
    &gt; cite a good reason
    &gt; to use these various access modifiers?  I guess I think 
    &gt; in Smalltalk too
    &gt; much, where everything is &quot;public&quot; and the idea of 
    &gt; private is only in
    &gt; comment form.  I am not saying that package-protected is 
    &gt; inherently bad, I
    &gt; just haven&#39;t seen a good deal of need for it.  I have 
    &gt; used it in some
    &gt; designs, where I wanted subclasses to override member 
    &gt; variables or member
    &gt; methods, but in those cases the overriding is still 
    &gt; tested through the
    &gt; parent class&#39;s public interface.
    &gt; 
    &gt; Example:
    &gt; 
    &gt; public abstract class AbstractParentClass{
    &gt; 	protected String name;
    &gt; 	protected String description;
    &gt; 	protected Schema schema;
    &gt; 
    &gt; 	protected AbstractParentClass(Schema aSchema){
    &gt; 		schema = aSchema;
    &gt; 	}
    &gt; 	public Information getInformation(){
    &gt; 		return new Information(name, description);
    &gt; 	}
    &gt; 	protected processSchema(){
    &gt; 		...
    &gt; 	}
    &gt; }
    &gt; 
    &gt; public class ConcreteClassA{
    &gt; 	private Schema schema;
    &gt; }
    &gt; 
    &gt; public class ConcreteClassB{
    &gt; }
    &gt; 	
    &gt; 
