    &gt;     &gt; &gt; 
    &gt;     &gt; &gt; IMO...
    &gt;     &gt; &gt; 
    &gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; It simply make testing easier, without changing the 
    &gt;     &gt; &gt; protection of
    &gt;     &gt; &gt; existing code. 
    &gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; We find it sometimes easy to test part of a flow 
    &gt;     &gt; (which usually
    &gt;     &gt; &gt; resides in a separate method) rather than 
    &gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; check the public interface function. 
    &gt;     &gt; &gt; 
    &gt;     &gt; &gt; Then shouldn&#39;t these be made part of the public 
    &gt; interface and 
    &gt;     &gt; &gt; allow the
    &gt;     &gt; &gt; client to interact with them?  If the client has 
    &gt; no business 
    &gt;     &gt; &gt; touching these
    &gt;     &gt; &gt; parts, make them private.
    &gt;     &gt; &gt; 
    &gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; Also, I take the term &quot;public interface&quot; as 
    &gt; relative. 
    &gt;     &gt; &gt; If an object
    &gt;     &gt; &gt; exposes an interface (set of methods)
    &gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; to its peer objects within its package, I 
    &gt; see no reason 
    &gt;     &gt; &gt; not to test
    &gt;     &gt; &gt; it, even though those methods are
    &gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; package-protected. 
    &gt;     &gt; &gt; 
    &gt;     &gt; &gt; I guess I disagree here.  I am not convinced that 
    &gt;     &gt; &gt; package-potected methods
    &gt;     &gt; &gt; are part of a public interface.  If they are used 
    &gt; that way I 
    &gt;     &gt; &gt; would question
    &gt;     &gt; &gt; whether some refactoring needed to take place.  
    &gt; But that&#39;s 
    &gt;     &gt; &gt; just my opinion.
    &gt;     &gt; &gt; I don&#39;t want to seem like I am picking on your 
    &gt; design decisions.
    &gt;     &gt; &gt; 
